{
  "title": "PyTorch",
  "content": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>PyTorch is a Python-based deep learning library that runs on CPU by default and supports GPU acceleration using </span><a href=\"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/cpp/cuda-tutorial/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><span>CUDA</span></a><span>. It follows a define-by-run approach, creating dynamic computation graphs during execution, which makes debugging and customization easier.</span></p><ul><li value=\"1\"><span>Uses dynamic graphs for flexibility</span></li><li value=\"2\"><span>Provides automatic differentiation for gradient computation</span></li><li value=\"3\"><span>Supports GPU acceleration with CUDA</span></li></ul><figure class=\"image\"><img alt=\"pytorch\" height=\"351\" src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260501150534016502/pytorch.webp\" srcset=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260501150534016502/pytorch.webp 652w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260501150534016502/pytorch-100.webp 100w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260501150534016502/pytorch-200.webp 200w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260501150534016502/pytorch-300.webp 300w\" width=\"652\"/><figcaption>Pytorch</figcaption></figure><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>PyTorch can be installed on Windows, macOS and Linux using pip for CPU (without GPU): </span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>pip install torch torchvision torchaudio</span></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>If you want to install in notebooks (Jupyter Notebook or Google Colab):</span></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>!pip install torch torchvision torchaudio</span></p></blockquote><h2 id=\"pytorch-tensors\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>PyTorch Tensors</span></h2><p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/python/tensors-in-pytorch/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><span>Tensors</span></a><span> are the fundamental data structures in PyTorch, similar to NumPy arrays but with GPU acceleration capabilities. PyTorch tensors support automatic differentiation, making them suitable for deep learning tasks.</span></p>[GFGTABS]<gfg-tabs data-mode=\"light\" data-run-ide=\"false\">\n            <gfg-tab slot=\"tab\">Python</gfg-tab>\n<gfg-panel slot=\"panel\" data-code-lang=\"python3\" data-main-code-start=\"None\" data-main-code-end=\"None\">\n    <code class=\"language-python3\"><div class=highlight><pre><span></span><span class=kn>import</span> <span class=nn>torch</span>\n\n<span class=n>x</span> <span class=o>=</span> <span class=n>torch</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>tensor</span><span class=p>([</span><span class=mf>1.0</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=mf>2.0</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=mf>3.0</span><span class=p>])</span>\n<span class=nb>print</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=s1>&#39;1D Tensor: </span><span class=se>\\n</span><span class=s1>&#39;</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=n>x</span><span class=p>)</span>\n\n<span class=n>y</span> <span class=o>=</span> <span class=n>torch</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>zeros</span><span class=p>((</span><span class=mi>3</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=mi>3</span><span class=p>))</span>\n<span class=nb>print</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=s1>&#39;2D Tensor: </span><span class=se>\\n</span><span class=s1>&#39;</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=n>y</span><span class=p>)</span>\n</pre></div></code>\n</gfg-panel></gfg-tabs>[/GFGTABS]<p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Output: </strong></b></p><figure class=\"image\"><img alt=\"pytorch\" height=\"248\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703154522165105/pytorch.png\" srcset=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703154522165105/pytorch.png 410w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703154522165105/pytorch-100.png 100w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703154522165105/pytorch-200.png 200w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703154522165105/pytorch-300.png 300w\" width=\"410\"/><figcaption>Output</figcaption></figure><h2 id=\"operations-on-tensors\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>Operations on Tensors</span></h2>[GFGTABS]<gfg-tabs data-mode=\"light\" data-run-ide=\"false\">\n            <gfg-tab slot=\"tab\">Python</gfg-tab>\n<gfg-panel slot=\"panel\" data-code-lang=\"python3\" data-main-code-start=\"None\" data-main-code-end=\"None\">\n    <code class=\"language-python3\"><div class=highlight><pre><span></span><span class=n>a</span> <span class=o>=</span> <span class=n>torch</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>tensor</span><span class=p>([</span><span class=mf>1.0</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=mf>2.0</span><span class=p>])</span>\n<span class=n>b</span> <span class=o>=</span> <span class=n>torch</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>tensor</span><span class=p>([</span><span class=mf>3.0</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=mf>4.0</span><span class=p>])</span>\n\n<span class=nb>print</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=s1>&#39;Element Wise Addition of a &amp; b: </span><span class=se>\\n</span><span class=s1>&#39;</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=n>a</span> <span class=o>+</span> <span class=n>b</span><span class=p>)</span>\n\n<span class=nb>print</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=s1>&#39;Matrix Multiplication of a &amp; b: </span><span class=se>\\n</span><span class=s1>&#39;</span><span class=p>,</span>\n      <span class=n>torch</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>matmul</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=n>a</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>view</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=mi>2</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=mi>1</span><span class=p>),</span> <span class=n>b</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>view</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=mi>1</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=mi>2</span><span class=p>)))</span>\n</pre></div></code>\n</gfg-panel></gfg-tabs>[/GFGTABS]<p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Output: </strong></b></p><figure class=\"image\"><img alt=\"pytorch\" height=\"202\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703154630183648/pytorch.png\" srcset=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703154630183648/pytorch.png 503w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703154630183648/pytorch-100.png 100w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703154630183648/pytorch-200.png 200w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703154630183648/pytorch-300.png 300w\" width=\"503\"/><figcaption>Output</figcaption></figure><h3 id=\"reshaping-and-transposing-tensors\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>Reshaping and Transposing Tensors</span></h3><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Both reshape() and view() change the shape of a tensor without changing its data. However, view() requires the tensor to be stored contiguously in memory, while reshape() can handle more cases by creating a copy when necessary.</span></p>[GFGTABS]<gfg-tabs data-mode=\"light\" data-run-ide=\"false\">\n            <gfg-tab slot=\"tab\">Python</gfg-tab>\n<gfg-panel slot=\"panel\" data-code-lang=\"python3\" data-main-code-start=\"None\" data-main-code-end=\"None\">\n    <code class=\"language-python3\"><div class=highlight><pre><span></span><span class=kn>import</span> <span class=nn>torch</span>\n<span class=n>t</span> <span class=o>=</span> <span class=n>torch</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>tensor</span><span class=p>([[</span><span class=mi>1</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=mi>2</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=mi>3</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=mi>4</span><span class=p>],</span>\n                 <span class=p>[</span><span class=mi>5</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=mi>6</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=mi>7</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=mi>8</span><span class=p>],</span>\n                 <span class=p>[</span><span class=mi>9</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=mi>10</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=mi>11</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=mi>12</span><span class=p>]])</span>\n\n<span class=nb>print</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=s2>&quot;Reshaping&quot;</span><span class=p>)</span>\n<span class=nb>print</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=n>t</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>reshape</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=mi>6</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=mi>2</span><span class=p>))</span>\n\n<span class=nb>print</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=s2>&quot;</span><span class=se>\\n</span><span class=s2>Transposing&quot;</span><span class=p>)</span>\n<span class=nb>print</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=n>t</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>transpose</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=mi>0</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=mi>1</span><span class=p>))</span>\n</pre></div></code>\n</gfg-panel></gfg-tabs>[/GFGTABS]<p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Output: </strong></b></p><figure class=\"image\"><img alt=\"pytorch\" height=\"615\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703154750629680/pytorch.png\" srcset=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703154750629680/pytorch.png 556w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703154750629680/pytorch-100.png 90w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703154750629680/pytorch-200.png 181w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703154750629680/pytorch-300.png 271w\" width=\"556\"/><figcaption>Output</figcaption></figure><h2 id=\"autograd-and-computational-graphs\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>Autograd &amp; Computational Graphs</span></h2><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>The autograd module automates gradient calculation for backpropagation. This is important in training deep neural networks.</span></p>[GFGTABS]<gfg-tabs data-mode=\"light\" data-run-ide=\"false\">\n            <gfg-tab slot=\"tab\">Python</gfg-tab>\n<gfg-panel slot=\"panel\" data-code-lang=\"python3\" data-main-code-start=\"None\" data-main-code-end=\"None\">\n    <code class=\"language-python3\"><div class=highlight><pre><span></span><span class=n>x</span> <span class=o>=</span> <span class=n>torch</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>tensor</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=mf>2.0</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=n>requires_grad</span><span class=o>=</span><span class=kc>True</span><span class=p>)</span>\n<span class=n>y</span> <span class=o>=</span> <span class=n>x</span> <span class=o>**</span> <span class=mi>2</span>\n<span class=n>y</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>backward</span><span class=p>()</span>\n<span class=nb>print</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=n>x</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>grad</span><span class=p>)</span>\n</pre></div></code>\n</gfg-panel></gfg-tabs>[/GFGTABS]<p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Output: </strong></b></p><blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>tensor(4.)</span></p></blockquote><p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Explanation: </strong></b></p><ul><li value=\"1\"><span>y = x ** 2 computes the square of x and records the operation in the computational graph.</span></li><li value=\"2\"><span>y.backward() performs backpropagation and calculates the gradient of y with respect to x.</span></li><li value=\"3\"><span>Since y = x\u00b2, its derivative is dy/dx = 2x.</span></li><li value=\"4\"><span>For x = 2, the gradient is 2 \u00d7 2 = 4, which is stored in x.grad.</span></li></ul><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>PyTorch dynamically creates a computational graph that tracks operations and gradients for backpropagation.</span></p><h2 id=\"building-neural-networks-in-pytorch\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>Building Neural Networks </span></h2><figure class=\"image\"><img alt=\"pytorch-workflow\" height=\"400\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260327182501650691/pytorch-workflow.webp\" srcset=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260327182501650691/pytorch-workflow.webp 800w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260327182501650691/pytorch-workflow-100.webp 100w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260327182501650691/pytorch-workflow-200.webp 200w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260327182501650691/pytorch-workflow-300.webp 300w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260327182501650691/pytorch-workflow-660.webp 660w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20260327182501650691/pytorch-workflow-768.webp 768w\" width=\"800\"/><figcaption>Pytorch Workflow</figcaption></figure><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>In PyTorch, neural networks are built using the </span><a href=\"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/deep-learning/understanding-torchnnparameter/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><span>torch.nn</span></a><span> module where:</span></p><ul><li value=\"1\"><b><strong>nn.Linear(in_features, out_features)</strong></b><span> defines a fully connected (dense) layer.</span></li><li value=\"2\"><span>Activation functions like torch.relu, torch.sigmoid or torch.softmax are applied between layers.</span></li><li value=\"3\"><b><strong>forward()</strong></b><span> method defines how data moves through the network.</span></li></ul><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>To build a neural network in PyTorch, we create a class that inherits from torch.nn.Module and defines its layers and forward pass.</span></p>[GFGTABS]<gfg-tabs data-mode=\"light\" data-run-ide=\"false\">\n            <gfg-tab slot=\"tab\">Python</gfg-tab>\n<gfg-panel slot=\"panel\" data-code-lang=\"python3\" data-main-code-start=\"None\" data-main-code-end=\"None\">\n    <code class=\"language-python3\"><div class=highlight><pre><span></span><span class=kn>import</span> <span class=nn>torch</span>\n<span class=kn>import</span> <span class=nn>torch.nn</span> <span class=k>as</span> <span class=nn>nn</span>\n\n\n<span class=k>class</span> <span class=nc>NeuralNetwork</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=n>nn</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>Module</span><span class=p>):</span>\n    <span class=k>def</span> <span class=fm>__init__</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=bp>self</span><span class=p>):</span>\n        <span class=nb>super</span><span class=p>()</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=fm>__init__</span><span class=p>()</span>\n        <span class=bp>self</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>fc1</span> <span class=o>=</span> <span class=n>nn</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>Linear</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=mi>10</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=mi>16</span><span class=p>)</span>\n        <span class=bp>self</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>fc2</span> <span class=o>=</span> <span class=n>nn</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>Linear</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=mi>16</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=mi>8</span><span class=p>)</span>\n        <span class=bp>self</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>fc3</span> <span class=o>=</span> <span class=n>nn</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>Linear</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=mi>8</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=mi>1</span><span class=p>)</span>\n\n    <span class=k>def</span> <span class=nf>forward</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=bp>self</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=n>x</span><span class=p>):</span>\n        <span class=n>x</span> <span class=o>=</span> <span class=n>torch</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>relu</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=bp>self</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>fc1</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=n>x</span><span class=p>))</span>\n        <span class=n>x</span> <span class=o>=</span> <span class=n>torch</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>relu</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=bp>self</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>fc2</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=n>x</span><span class=p>))</span>\n        <span class=n>x</span> <span class=o>=</span> <span class=n>torch</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>sigmoid</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=bp>self</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>fc3</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=n>x</span><span class=p>))</span>\n        <span class=k>return</span> <span class=n>x</span>\n\n\n<span class=n>model</span> <span class=o>=</span> <span class=n>NeuralNetwork</span><span class=p>()</span>\n<span class=nb>print</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=n>model</span><span class=p>)</span>\n</pre></div></code>\n</gfg-panel></gfg-tabs>[/GFGTABS]<p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Output: </strong></b></p><figure class=\"image\"><img alt=\"pytorch\" height=\"183\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703155123039186/pytorch.png\" srcset=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703155123039186/pytorch.png 924w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703155123039186/pytorch-100.png 100w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703155123039186/pytorch-200.png 200w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703155123039186/pytorch-300.png 300w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703155123039186/pytorch-660.png 660w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703155123039186/pytorch-768.png 768w\" width=\"924\"/><figcaption>Output</figcaption></figure><h3 id=\"define-loss-function-and-optimizer\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>Define Loss Function and Optimizer</span></h3><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Once model is defined, it needs to specify:</span></p><ul><li value=\"1\"><span>A loss function to measure the error.</span></li><li value=\"2\"><span>An optimizer to update the weights based on computed gradients.</span></li></ul><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>We use nn.BCELoss() for binary cross-entropy loss and used optim.Adam() for Adam optimizer to combine the benefits of momentum and adaptive learning rates. </span></p>[GFGTABS]<gfg-tabs data-mode=\"light\" data-run-ide=\"false\">\n            <gfg-tab slot=\"tab\">Python</gfg-tab>\n<gfg-panel slot=\"panel\" data-code-lang=\"python3\" data-main-code-start=\"None\" data-main-code-end=\"None\">\n    <code class=\"language-python3\"><div class=highlight><pre><span></span><span class=n>model</span> <span class=o>=</span> <span class=n>NeuralNetwork</span><span class=p>()</span>\n<span class=n>criterion</span> <span class=o>=</span> <span class=n>nn</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>BCELoss</span><span class=p>()</span>  \n<span class=n>optimizer</span> <span class=o>=</span> <span class=n>torch</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>optim</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>Adam</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=n>model</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>parameters</span><span class=p>(),</span> <span class=n>lr</span><span class=o>=</span><span class=mf>0.01</span><span class=p>)</span>\n</pre></div></code>\n</gfg-panel></gfg-tabs>[/GFGTABS]<h3 id=\"train-the-model\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>Train the Model</span></h3><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>The training involves generating dummy data (100 samples, each with 10 features). After this we run a training loop where we:</span></p><ul><li value=\"1\"><span>optimizer.zero_grad() clears the accumulated gradients from the previous step.</span></li><li value=\"2\"><span>Forward Pass (model(inputs)) passes inputs through the model to generate predictions.</span></li><li value=\"3\"><span>Loss Computation (criterion(outputs, targets)) computes the difference between predictions and actual labels. </span></li><li value=\"4\"><span>Backpropagation (loss.backward()) computes gradients for all weights.</span></li><li value=\"5\"><span>Optimizer Step (optimizer.step()) updates the weights based on the computed gradients.</span></li></ul>[GFGTABS]<gfg-tabs data-mode=\"light\" data-run-ide=\"false\">\n            <gfg-tab slot=\"tab\">Python</gfg-tab>\n<gfg-panel slot=\"panel\" data-code-lang=\"python3\" data-main-code-start=\"None\" data-main-code-end=\"None\">\n    <code class=\"language-python3\"><div class=highlight><pre><span></span><span class=n>inputs</span> <span class=o>=</span> <span class=n>torch</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>randn</span><span class=p>((</span><span class=mi>100</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=mi>10</span><span class=p>))</span>\n<span class=n>targets</span> <span class=o>=</span> <span class=n>torch</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>randint</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=mi>0</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=mi>2</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=p>(</span><span class=mi>100</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=mi>1</span><span class=p>))</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>float</span><span class=p>()</span>\n<span class=n>epochs</span> <span class=o>=</span> <span class=mi>20</span>\n\n<span class=k>for</span> <span class=n>epoch</span> <span class=ow>in</span> <span class=nb>range</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=n>epochs</span><span class=p>):</span>\n    <span class=n>optimizer</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>zero_grad</span><span class=p>()</span>\n    <span class=n>outputs</span> <span class=o>=</span> <span class=n>model</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=n>inputs</span><span class=p>)</span>\n    <span class=n>loss</span> <span class=o>=</span> <span class=n>criterion</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=n>outputs</span><span class=p>,</span> <span class=n>targets</span><span class=p>)</span>\n    <span class=n>loss</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>backward</span><span class=p>()</span>\n    <span class=n>optimizer</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>step</span><span class=p>()</span>\n\n    <span class=k>if</span> <span class=p>(</span><span class=n>epoch</span> <span class=o>+</span> <span class=mi>1</span><span class=p>)</span> <span class=o>%</span> <span class=mi>5</span> <span class=o>==</span> <span class=mi>0</span><span class=p>:</span>\n        <span class=nb>print</span><span class=p>(</span><span class=sa>f</span><span class=s2>&quot;Epoch [</span><span class=si>{</span><span class=n>epoch</span><span class=o>+</span><span class=mi>1</span><span class=si>}</span><span class=s2>/</span><span class=si>{</span><span class=n>epochs</span><span class=si>}</span><span class=s2>], Loss: </span><span class=si>{</span><span class=n>loss</span><span class=o>.</span><span class=n>item</span><span class=p>()</span><span class=si>:</span><span class=s2>.4f</span><span class=si>}</span><span class=s2>&quot;</span><span class=p>)</span>\n</pre></div></code>\n</gfg-panel></gfg-tabs>[/GFGTABS]<p dir=\"ltr\"><b><strong>Output: </strong></b></p><figure class=\"image\"><img alt=\"pytorch\" height=\"164\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703155301311941/pytorch.png\" srcset=\"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703155301311941/pytorch.png 449w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703155301311941/pytorch-100.png 100w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703155301311941/pytorch-200.png 200w,https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20250703155301311941/pytorch-300.png 300w\" width=\"449\"/><figcaption>Output</figcaption></figure><h2 id=\"pytorch-vs-tensorflow\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>PyTorch vs. TensorFlow</span></h2><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Lets see a quick difference between pytorch and </span><a href=\"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/python/introduction-to-tensorflow/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><span>tensorflow</span></a><span>:</span></p><table><thead><tr><th><span>Feature</span></th><th><span>PyTorch</span></th><th><span>TensorFlow</span></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><th><span>Computational Graph</span></th><td><span>Dynamic</span></td><td><span>Dynamic (Eager Execution by Default)</span></td></tr><tr><th><span>Ease of Use</span></th><td><span>Pythonic, easy to debug</span></td><td><span>Steeper learning curve</span></td></tr><tr><th><span>Performance</span></th><td><span>Fast with eager execution</span></td><td><span>Optimized for large-scale deployment</span></td></tr><tr><th><span>Deployment</span></th><td><span>TorchScript &amp; ONNX</span></td><td><span>TensorFlow Serving &amp; TensorFlow Lite</span></td></tr><tr><th><span>Popularity in Research</span></th><td><span>Widely used</span></td><td><span>Also widely used but more in production</span></td></tr></tbody></table><h2 id=\"applications-of-pytorch\" style=\"text-align:left\"><span>Applications</span></h2><ul><li value=\"1\"><b><strong>Computer Vision</strong></b><span>: Widely used in image classification, object detection and segmentation using CNNs and Transformers (e.g., ViT).</span></li><li value=\"2\"><b><strong>Natural Language Processing (NLP)</strong></b><span>: Supports transformers, recurrent neural networks (RNNs) and LSTMs for applications like text generation and sentiment analysis.</span></li><li value=\"3\"><b><strong>Reinforcement Learning</strong></b><span>: Used in Deep Q-Networks (DQN), Policy Gradient Methods and Actor-Critic Algorithms.</span></li></ul>",
